how to resolve this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Java ClassLoader setup**\\n\\nI'm thinking about placing Java source under `src/testPrimary/java`, with a custom Gradle sourceSet that doesn't interfere with test runtime. Maybe compiling it separately and loading with URLClassLoader in the test is a good route? I wonder if that's too broad. \\n\\nThe test can utilize URLs for necessary components like the micrometer-core jar and test fixture outputs. It seems I need a child-first ClassLoader for certain dependencies, but that might introduce complexities like using reflection or method handles for dynamic class access.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating classloader and testing options**\\n\\nI'm considering executing library class bytecode, possibly something like TrackDynamicAccess records. I'm worried that direct reflection in tests might be disallowed, but accessing the public API from a child classloader could be a workaround due to testing classloader isolation. However, that feels risky. \\n\\nPerhaps a separate sourceSet and a JUnit test that forks a new Java process with a different classpath would be more straightforward. But, hmm, tests under a native image shouldn't spawn a Java process, right? That's not ideal.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing class usage**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I need to include all primary classes. I see that the existing Hazelcast3's LocalMapStats and NearCacheStats are still relevant. The current tests are importing com.hazelcast.core.IMap and creating an old IMap proxy. However, I notice that the HazelcastIMapAdapter CLASS_I_MAP is now the primary fixture for com.hazelcast.map.IMap. I just need to figure out the best way to proceed with this setup!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_anMgAp6vDGj2JeYfYVcxh0aX|fc_07970394a73d0df90169f11cb141e08197b76f847dae08376d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "git status --short && git log --oneline -3", "timeout